Student Performance Data Analysis Report

Author

Zuoming Hu

1 Introduction

1.1 Background and context

Student academic performance directly impacts academic advancement and employment, and also provides a basis for school resource allocation and teaching improvements. Data for 2,392 students were considered in this analysis. The dependent variable is GPA (0â4 scale), and GradeClass is used for grouping purposes only. The primary independent variables under consideration are study duration weekly, absences, and the family support variables (tutoring, parental, and extracurricular/sports/music/volunteering). Factors considered in the background variables including gender, ethnicity, and level of education of the parents are age.

1.2 Research question and hypotheses

How much of an impact do study behavior and family support have on GPA, controlling for the background variables? H1: Time spent studying and GPA are positively related; H2: Absences and GPA are inversely related; H3: Participation in tutoring and higher parental support are positively correlated with GPA; H4: The impact of extracurricular activities on GPA is heterogeneous (to be tested in direction).

1.3 Report structure

Section 2 describes the data and the cleaning process; Section 3 provides the descriptive statistics as well as EDA; Section 4 details the methods and the diagnostics, including a comparison of the OLS and Lasso approaches; Section 5 delivers the results and an executive summary at the start; Section 6 analyzes the findings and their limitations; Section 7 offers the conclusion along with policy recommendations. This is followed by references and appendices.

2 Data Description

2.1 Dataset size and variables

Description of the data In this study, we utilize de-identified student data (N = 2,392). Individual students are the unit of analysis, and the outcome variable is the GPA (on a 0-4 scale). We examine predictors pertaining to academic performance: study time per week, absences, parental education, tutoring, parental support, and participation in extracurricular activities (i.e., sports, music, volunteering). Gender and ethnicity are controlled to account for potential background differences and reduce confounding bias. The data dictionary for the chosen variables is generated automatically by the code below.

2.3 Data cleaning/preprocessing steps

During the preprocessing phase, we examined each variable for missing values, ranges, and completeness, confirming that all values fell within reasonable ranges. The data was complete and ready for immediate use. We then recoded the numeric values for categorical variables into labeled factors for better readability and easier reference group setting and coefficient interpretations. Gender included the labels Male and Female; ethnicity was simplified to Caucasian, African American, Asian, and Other; parental education was grouped as None, High School, Some College, Bachelor, and Higher; tutoring and participation in extracurricular activities were categorized as No and Yes; and parental support was classified as None, Low, Moderate, High, and Very High. GradeClass was for grouping and quality assurance purposes only and was excluded from the regression modeling. For coefficient interpretability, the main analysis was kept on the original scale, while continuous variables were standardized to z-scores for comparison across models, particularly in Lasso.

Average GPAs within the support categories showed family support climbing from âNoneâ to âVery Highâ (1.54 â 2.19). 3.5 Summary of Key Insights

Study time, attendance, family support, and academic engagement all likely predict a studentâs GPA, while the influence of parentsâ education level is minimal. Such findings would be informative for the following regression analyses, indicating that the examination of the linear effect of these variables on academic performance would be appropriate.

4 Methodology

4.1 Model Construction and Variable Selection

Utilizing studentsâ GPAs as the dependent variable, the study undertook the construction of multiple linear regression and lasso regression models to analyze the effects of family factors and learning behaviors on academic performance. Weekly study time, number of unscheduled absences, family support, tutoring and extracurricular activity involvement, and gender were classified as independent variables. These predictors were chosen based on hypotheses (H1âH4) discussed earlier which state that study time will be positively correlated with GPA, absences will be negatively correlated with GPA, and family support alongside the expectations of academic engagement will positively influence academic performance.

4.2 Lasso Regression Technique and Model Evaluation Criteria

Lasso regression utilizes L1 regularization to simplify the model while performing variable selection. Subsequently, 10-fold cross-validation helps in determining the optimal Î». Models are compared and their performance determined based on Mean Sequence Error (MSE) and Mean Average Error (MAE). It was evident that the Lasso model delivered lower MAE, hence portraying the Lasso model as overall more robust. In addition to this, the model independently keeps the most important variables (study time, absences, parental support, and tutoring) which enhances conciseness and interpretability.

Figure 11: 10-Fold Cross-Validation for Lasso Regression

4.3 Model Fitting and Diagnostic Testing

The results of the OLS model fit show that the RÂ² equaled 0.9408 and the adjusted RÂ² was 0.9406, which means that the variance of the GPA returns was approximately 94% explained by the model. To improve predictive robustness while avoiding overfitting, the Lasso model was constructed with a 10-fold cross validation along with Î»min = 0.0009, the optimal penalty parameter. To test that the regression model satisfies the classical linear regression assumptions, I constructed residual diagnostic plots. Most importantly, the residual-fit plot shows good homogeneity of variance, the QQ plot is almost diagonal, the scale-location plot shows no outliers and, the leverage and VIFs, which are both below 2, show no multicollinearity.

Model comparison showed that OLS produced Lasso models with MSEs of 0.04952 and 0.04955, respectively, and MAEs of 0.1779 and 0.1781, respectively, with very similar errors. The OLS model is best based on MSE, while the Lasso model is more stable based on MAE. Since the Lasso model is less sensitive to outliers, I prefer it for the final prediction model. This choice is based on the Lasso modelâs overall accuracy and generalizability.

5 Results

5.1 Executive Summary

The data shows that class participation, absenteeism, and family support are among the primary determinants affecting student GPA. Every absence account for a drop of 0.10 in GPA. On the other hand, every additional hour spent studying a week translates to an increase of 0.03 to their GPA. With respect to family support, the positive effects are more pronounced the greater that support is, though effects are still present at lower levels.Â The accuracy of the OLS and Lasso methods is similar (RÂ²â0.94, MAEâ0.18), providing consistent evidence for the main conclusions. Although OLS models should be reported for ease of interpretation and communication, for practical use, more emphasis should be placed on Lasso, as it will yield a more streamlined selection of variables under error approximation. Thus, we recommend that resources be prioritized for attendance warning and intervention (to mitigate the considerable negative impact of absences), consolidation of weekly study time (to achieve small but incremental improvements), and enhancement of home-school partnership and tutoring alignment to tackle substantial grade improvements in the first few weeks of the semester.

We fitted two models: OLS and Lasso. OLS explains 94.08% of GPA variance (Adj-RÂ² 0.9406) with MSE 0.04952 and MAE 0.1779. Lasso, tuned by 10-fold CV at Î»_min â 0.0009, yields MSE 0.04956 and MAE 0.1781âessentially the same error with fewer predictors (see Table 9). Tuning supports this choice: the CV curve drops then flattens; Î»_min and Î»_1se lie on the plateau, so we can cut complexity without losing accuracy and with no overfitting. We report OLS for interpretation and prefer Lasso for deployment.

Diagnostics indicate no issues with the assumptions (see Figures 12â13): the residuals do not show a funnel pattern; the QQ plot points follow the 45Â° line closely; the scale-location and leverage plots indicate only a few high-leverage cases; and all the VIFs are under 2. This shows that the model is reliable and is well specified.

The main indicators are consistent across different predictions (refer to Table 10). The most significant negative influence are absences (â -0.10 GPA for each absence). The positive influence of study time is also modest (â +0.03 for every hour studied). The effect of parental support increases systematically from Low to Very High. There are positive associations with GPA for tutoring and extracurricular activities (â +0.25 and +0.19 respectively). The impact of gender (female) becomes irrelevant after controlling for other factors. These findings are consistent with previous descriptive trends; the main factors are attendance, study effort, and parental support and resources.

Given the similar error levels in Table 9, deploy Lasso for a more compact, easier to maintain model, and use OLS to communicate the effects as shown in Table 10. Prioritize attendance alerts and timely interventions first (avoiding one absence â +0.10 GPA), then stable weekly study routines (+0.03 for every extra hour), and more robust homeâschool coordination and tutoring for at-risk students.

5.3 Implications of the Results

Set the sequence of actions as attendance first, then study hours, then family/tutoring.Â Start with reminders, mentor check-ins, and school-home contact to get high-absence students back on track. Afterwards, establish a weekly study schedule. Instruct on time management techniques and determine certain study periods. Studies have shown that light monitoring with brief, frequent practice sessions enhance study efficiency. After this, reinforce tutoring and extracurricular activities, and seek for parental involvement to create a consistent learning atmosphere. Role models are apparent. To obtain a lean risk score that is simple to implement and manage, use Lasso as the operations models for risk; on the communications side, use OLS to create visuals (dashboards/key-point charts) that show the marginal effect and importance of each element to assist teachers and parents in understanding. Maintain a weekly rhythm with an active focus for the first 3-4 weeks. The primary KPIs will focus on monitoring attendance, study hours per week, and measuring the GPA increase. Working with students the model marks as high risk first, then adjust the weekly objectives to show clear, consistent progress.

6 Discussion

6.1 Validation of Key Hypotheses

The study substantiated the principal hypotheses H1âH3. Academic engagement and family support are substantial determinants of studentsâ GPAs, while absenteeism significantly deteriorates academic performance. The correlation between attendance and study time with grades supports the educational psychology theory correlating academic engagement and performance. The effects of parental support and academic tutoring also suggest the importance of the family environment in student learning outcomes.

6.2 Interpretation of Extracurricular and Background Factors

In H4, extracurricular activities exhibited a positive, albeit weak, impact. This might illustrate that extracurricular activities are mainly focused on facilitating social engagement and comprehensive abilities, and that their impact on performance activities and net academic changes may be peripheral, or hinge on the type of activity and the amount of time devoted to it. Also, the lack of significance of background factors, such as gender and educational attainment of parents, suggest that the grades variations are primarily due to the changes in modifiable learning behaviors and not the âhardâ social structures.

6.3 Limitations and Future Considerations

While the high fit of the model is acknowledged, it is important to point out the weaknesses of the model. First, the cross-sectional nature of the data and the absence of more complex control variables, the unique explanatory value of causal assertions, and the self-report variables that could be impacted by subjective bias. Lastly, absence of possible factors on the model, such as learning motivation, psychological well-being, and the quality of the teacher, may not allow the model to fully develop its explanatory capability. More longitudinal research and additional psychosocial variables could aid in further elucidating the results, particularly in the case of the more dynamic effects of learning engagement and learning design support in the family on academic outcomes.

7 Conclusion

This study examined the influence that academic engagement, attendance, and family support have on grade point average (GPA) using data from 2,392 students. Study time, absences, and parental support emerged as the greatest predictors of GPA: more study time and greater parental support correlated with higher academic achievement, while absences correlated with lower achievement. Comparative analyses and model diagnostics confirmed the consistency of the OLS and Lasso model outputs, which validated the defense of the research conclusions.

These findings suggest the importance of research behavioral factors. The support from family and the school is of utmost importance in achieving academic success. Practitioners in education should prioritize strategies that enhance studentsâ study habits and academic engagement, absences, and strengthen school-parent partnerships, including targeted tutoring and homework assistance.

Additionally, the research could analyze psychological variables, motivation, and social-economic status together with data on teacher effectiveness, in order to study the performance variables from a longitudinal perspective and provide policymakers with data on academic performance.

  • Lasso Regression and Model Comparison
Code 
X <- model.matrix(form_full, data = data)[, -1]
y <- data$GPA

set.seed(123)
cv_lasso <- cv.glmnet(X, y, alpha = 1, nfolds = 10, standardize = TRUE)

lambda_min <- cv_lasso$lambda.min
lambda_1se <- cv_lasso$lambda.1se

pred_lm <- predict(model_lm, newdata = data)
mse_lm <- mean((data$GPA - pred_lm)^2)
mae_lm <- mean(abs(data$GPA - pred_lm))
